Yet this and the next before it, haue some connexion:
vers. 13. the former being of the inconuenience
that commeth by a bad wife;

Yea let them hence learne what they owe vnto God, whom God hath vouchsafed such a blessing vnto. Hath God bestowed such a Wife on thee, as Salomon here speaketh of? It is a pretious Iewell; such as thy Father could neuer leaue thee. It is a greater Treasure then the greatest Prince on earth, then the mightiest Monarch in the world is able to bequeath to his Heire. We see how Parents are oft troubled in making search for their Sonnes, and yet when they haue done their best endeuour, misse of that they desire. We might here rise by degrees on the better side, as we did before on the worse. As euils, so good things, the more inward the greater. AProv. 17. 2. & 14. 35 Luk. 12. 42. 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . Menand. 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . Eurip. Mel • agr. De beneficijs ac fide servorū in Domin • s, consule sis Senec. de benef. l. 3. c. 18. 27. Et Valer. Max. l 6. c. 8. trusty seruant is no small blessing; a
