Prov. 10. 1. & v. 20. & 17 6. & 23. 15. 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 . Menand. a wise sonne yet a greater; and a prudent wife the greatest of all: a greater blessing then any of the former, that yet for temporall blessings may seeme of the greatest. And how do maried persons then stand engaged to God aboue others, whom he hath blessed in their choise? A great measure of thankfulnes owe they vnto him, proportionable in some sort to the blessing bestowed on them.

Note thirdly from hence,3. Doctr. that Christ Iesus is no enemie to honest mirth & delight, at such meetings and solemnities as this, but hath by his owne presence and precedent approued it. Though we doe not read in the Scripture, that Christ euer laughed, yet we neede not thinke that he was so rigide and austere, that he could indure no mirth and delight;
As though men in his Presence were in their silent dumps, and made dumbe shewes onely one to another. Surely then would not Christ haue bin so often invited to Feasts as he was; or if he had, he would not haue frequented them so often: For the speciall vse of Feasts are for frends to rejoyce and make merry togither in; and therefore in the Holy Tongue haue their
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 Chaggim. name, from leaping and rejoycing.
